veloped by women of color activists, Kao highlights the importance of experience in feminist methodology and Christian ethics. She shows what surrogacy is like from the perspective of women becoming pregnant for others, parents who have opted for surrogacy (including queer couples), and the surrogate-born children themselves. Developing a constructive framework of ethical norms and principles to guide the formation of surrogacy relationships, Kao ultimately offers a vision for surrogacy that celebrates the reproductive generosity and solidarity displayed through the sharing of traditionally maternal roles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian ethics. 0aFeminist ethics. 0aSurrogate motherhoodxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aSurrogate motherhoodxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Christian Life / Family.2bisacsh  aBible.  aChristianity.  aassisted reproductive technology (ART).  afeminism.  ain vitro fertilization (IVF).  aparenthood.  apregnancy.  areproductive justice.  asurrogacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023z9783111318820oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363598240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503635982423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503635982/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-P